Explanations on global competitiveness
In November, the World Economic Forum and the Center for International Development at Harvard University published the Global Competitiveness Report (Competitiveness Report) for the year 2001.
In the study covering 75 countries, Finland, the United States, and Canada take the top three positions, while Nicaragua, Nigeria, and Zimbabwe form the bottom tier.
(All rankings can be found at www.weforum.com.)
As a co-responsible leader of this annual study, I am often asked what competitiveness actually means.
Is there also economic competition among the countries besides the military one?
Does it even make sense to say that Finland is more competitive than, for example, Germany or Italy?
In our report, competitiveness is defined very precisely: namely as the ability of a country to achieve sustainable economic growth over the medium term – that is, over a period of five years.
This definition, however, does not mean that the competitiveness of one country simultaneously says something about the lack of competitiveness of another country.
With better political strategies, all countries on Earth could simultaneously achieve higher growth.
Nevertheless, it is useful to create a ranking of countries in terms of their growth potential.
Every country is interested in finding out whether its political strategies and public institutions can keep pace with those of other countries in terms of their ability to achieve sustainable economic growth.
In many respects, economic growth is comparable to a sporting competition, in which the gains of one country or region come at the expense of another country or region.
Countries compete, for example, for internationally mobile capital.
The more a country can gain from foreign direct investments, the less another country receives.
This becomes entirely clear when countries bid for a specific investment project.
When Intel plans a new semiconductor plant, various countries are invited to submit bids.
The competition for the award is fierce, and in many cases, countries also offer tax incentives, infrastructure improvements, and even adjustments to study programs at the local technical university.
In this year, we assessed a country's competitiveness (growth potential) based on three broad criteria: (1) Technology, (2) public institutions, and (3) macroeconomic stability.
For each of these categories, we identified indicators whose average values were calculated using a specific method to then create an overall growth and competitiveness index.
The criterion of technology refers to a country's ability to drive new developments and to apply technologies developed elsewhere.
Some countries such as the United States, Japan, South Korea, Israel, and Sweden invest heavily in research and development and thus achieve high scores in the area of innovation.
Other countries such as Argentina and Brazil invest less in research and development and therefore achieve little in terms of new products and processes.
Innovative countries benefit from these innovations and thus enjoy a high level of prosperity.
In this area, the United States, Canada, and Finland occupy the top three positions on the ranking list.
The criterion "public institutions" refers to the quality of the administration.
Is corruption a widespread problem?
Are the courts incorruptible and impartial?
Can one trust that the government will fulfill its obligations properly?
Countries with well-functioning public institutions achieve higher growth rates than countries with corrupt officials and decaying judges.
High ethical standards promote economic performance.
In this regard, the Nordic countries are leading globally, and Finland, Iceland, and Denmark are also the top performers on the ranking list.
Corruption is virtually unknown in these countries.
Macroeconomic stability is defined by the absence of inflation, a balanced state budget, a realistic exchange rate for the national currency, the ability of businesses and the government to obtain loans on the capital market, and high confidence that the government will fulfill its financial obligations.
Taking the example of Asia in the late 1990s, we have learned that a macroeconomic crisis can destroy economic growth, even if businesses are internationally competitive.
The three leading countries in terms of macroeconomic stability are Singapore, Ireland, and Switzerland.
In our studies on competitiveness, we have noticed that the world economy can be divided into two categories of countries: the innovation-friendly and the non-innovation-friendly.
Only about 20 countries are actively engaged in the development of new technologies.
In these countries, which are among the richest in the world, a superb system of technological innovations is considered a prerequisite for sustained competitiveness.
Universities must be excellent, state laboratories should reach world-class standards, and the government and industry should invest strongly in research and development.
A key factor for future growth in these economies is the proportion of students who, after completing compulsory education, proceed to higher schools and universities.
In the United States and Canada, this proportion is 80%.
For the "non-innovation-friendly" countries, technology is just as important, but most new technologies are imported from abroad and not developed within the country itself.
Some countries specialize in importing new technologies, while others do not.
In the past ten or fifteen years, a large part of the technology imports took place within the framework of foreign direct investments.
American companies that heavily invested in Mexico or Taiwanese companies that invested in mainland China also brought new technologies with them, which increased the efficiency of production in the respective economies of the target countries.
Therefore, it was entirely sensible for the concerned countries to make every effort to attract these foreign investments: they bring not only capital, but also new technologies.
A strength and at the same time a weakness of our analysis of competitiveness is that it is medium-term oriented and does not focus on the next one or two years.
Our rankings are not suitable for assessing short-term cyclical changes in an economy, but they do provide insight into the long-term prospects of the major economies.
It is therefore an irony that many of the countries that took the top positions this year, such as the United States or Singapore, are actually in a recession, while others, which are ranked further down, such as China (rank 39), are not affected by the global recession.
In part, the slowdown of the economy is linked to the terrorist attacks of September 11, but it is also increasingly clear that the American economy and other major economies connected to it through trade and production networks were already sliding into recession before September.
Nevertheless, we believe that this is a temporary cyclical downturn, and that the United States will regain its ability to achieve strong economic growth within the next five years.
